---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Teachers | 7-Day Phật Thất Retreat at Bodh Gaya">
    <section class="max-w-4xl py-16 space-y-10">
        <div>
            <p class="mb-3 text-sm tracking-[0.2em] uppercase text-neutral-500">Teachers</p>
            <h1 class="mb-6">Retreat Leadership</h1>
            <p class="max-w-3xl text-lg leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                The retreat is guided by monastics from Viên Giác Patriarchal Monastery and its affiliated monasteries in Europe, accompanying participants
                throughout the days of practice in Bodh Gaya. Viên Giác belongs to the Lâm Tế Chúc Thánh lineage, a branch of the Linji tradition, with a
                practice that integrates both Chan and Pure Land. In addition, all of the teachers have also studied other Buddhist traditions, enriching
                their own practice and broadening the way they guide others.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="grid gap-6">
            <article class="rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-6">
                <div class="grid gap-8 md:grid-cols-[260px_1fr] md:items-start">
                    <div class="overflow-hidden rounded-3xl border border-neutral-200 bg-white shadow-sm">
                        <img src="/images/hoathuongthichnhudien.png" alt="Hòa Thượng Thích Như Điển" class="h-[320px] w-full object-cover object-top" />
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <h2 class="mb-2">Hòa Thượng Thích Như Điển</h2>
                        <p class="mb-4 text-neutral-500">
                            Founding Figure of Viên Giác Monastery, Hannover – Germany, and teacher of Thầy Hạnh Tấn, Thầy Hạnh Bảo, Thầy Hạnh Định, and Thầy
                            Hạnh Giới
                        </p>
                        <p class="leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            Hòa Thượng Thích Như Điển is one of the most senior and influential Vietnamese Buddhist teachers in Europe. He belongs to the 41nd
                            generation of the Chúc Thánh branch of the Linji tradition. After completing extensive monastic training in Vietnam, receiving full
                            bhikshu ordination in 1971, and continuing higher studies in Japan in education and Buddhist studies, he came to Germany in the late
                            1970s and began laying the foundation for Vietnamese Buddhist life there. In 1978, he established Viên Giác as a place of practice
                            in Hannover, which later grew into one of the most important Vietnamese Buddhist centers in the diaspora.
                        </p>
                        <p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            Over several decades, Hòa Thượng has devoted himself to teaching, guiding monastics and lay practitioners, building Buddhist
                            institutions, and supporting the transmission of the Dharma across Europe. Under his leadership, Viên Giác developed into a major
                            religious and cultural center, drawing tens of thousands of visitors each year. He has also ordained and trained many disciples,
                            played a leading role in Vietnamese Buddhist organizations in Germany and Europe, and authored or translated numerous Buddhist
                            works. His long experience in teaching, leadership, and Dharma propagation continues to inspire generations of practitioners.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </article>

            <article class="rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-6">
                <div class="grid gap-8 md:grid-cols-[260px_1fr] md:items-start">
                    <div class="overflow-hidden rounded-3xl border border-neutral-200 bg-white shadow-sm">
                        <img src="/images/thayhanhtan.png" alt="Thầy Hạnh Tấn" class="h-[320px] w-full object-cover object-top" />
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <h2 class="mb-2">Thầy Hạnh Tấn</h2>
                        <p class="mb-4 text-neutral-500">Amitayus Monastery, Dippoldiswalde – Germany</p>
                        <p class="leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            Born in Vietnam in 1964, Thầy Hạnh Tấn arrived in Germany in 1979 as a refugee. After completing his secondary education, he entered
                            monastic training at Viên Giác Monastery in Hannover in 1986 and received novice ordination in 1987. In 1993, he received full
                            bhikshu ordination, completed a graduate degree in Religious Studies, and left Germany for India to further his Buddhist studies and
                            practice. He returned to Germany in 2000 and was formally appointed abbot of Viên Giác Monastery in Hannover three years later. In
                            2008, he stepped down from that position in order to pursue a long-term retreat aspiration in Asia. In 2010, he returned to Germany
                            and founded Amitayus Monastery near Dresden, where he currently serves as abbot. He belongs to the 42nd generation of the Chúc Thánh
                            branch of the Linji tradition
                        </p>
                        <p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            Thầy Hạnh Tấn belongs to a newer generation of monastics who received both a modern Western education and strong training in their
                            own Buddhist tradition. In his case, this is the Vietnamese and Chinese Mahāyāna tradition. In addition, he has also studied and
                            practiced methods from other Buddhist schools, including Satipaṭṭhāna and Vipassanā traditions from Thailand and Myanmar, although
                            the principal path he has pursued most deeply is Tibetan Vajrayāna practice.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </article>

            <article class="rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-6">
                <div class="grid gap-8 md:grid-cols-[260px_1fr] md:items-start">
                    <div class="overflow-hidden rounded-3xl border border-neutral-200 bg-white shadow-sm">
                        <img src="/images/thayhanhbao.jpg" alt="Thầy Hạnh Bảo" class="h-[320px] w-full object-cover object-top" />
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <h2 class="mb-2">Thầy Hạnh Bảo</h2>
                        <p class="leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            He belongs to the 42nd generation of the Chúc Thánh branch of the Linji tradition and is the third disciple of Hoà Thượng Thích Như
                            Điển. He came to Germany at a young age to study and later entered Viên Giác Monastery to become a monk in 1991. He received novice
                            ordination on July 25, 1991, and full bhikshu ordination on July 30, 1994. His practice is rooted mainly in the Vietnamese Buddhist
                            tradition, especially Pure Land Buddhism.
                        </p>
                        <p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            He is currently the abbot of Liên Tâm Monastery in Turku, Finland, and Viên Ý Pagoda in Italy. Over the years, he has taught Buddha
                            Dharma widely in Vietnamese communities in Vietnam, the United States, South Korea, and Europe, and is well known as an experienced
                            Dharma teacher. He also served as abbot of Vạn Hạnh Pagoda in Denmark for ten years and has been an elected member of the executive
                            committee of the World Buddhist Sangha Council since 2002.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </article>

            <article class="rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-6">
                <div class="grid gap-8 md:grid-cols-[260px_1fr] md:items-start">
                    <div class="overflow-hidden rounded-3xl border border-neutral-200 bg-white shadow-sm">
                        <img src="/images/thayhanhdinh.jpg" alt="Thầy Hạnh Định" class="h-[320px] w-full object-cover object-top" />
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <h2 class="mb-2">Thầy Hạnh Định</h2>
                        <p class="mb-4 text-neutral-500">
                            Abbot of Phật Linh Pagoda, Bà Rịa–Vũng Tàu – Vietnam, and current abbot of Viên Giác Patriarchal Monastery, Hannover – Germany
                        </p>
                        <p class="leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            Born in 1972, Thầy Hạnh Định entered monastic life at Viên Giác Monastery in Hannover in 1997 after years of Buddhist practice in
                            Norway, where he had taken refuge with Hòa thượng Thích Trí Minh at Khuông Việt Pagoda. He received novice ordination in 1998 and
                            full bhikshu ordination in 2001. In 2003, he was appointed to serve at the Viên Giác Study Center in India while also helping
                            oversee Buddhist activities connected with Phật Linh Pagoda in Vietnam.
                        </p>
                        <p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            In 2006, he returned to Vietnam to directly supervise the major restoration of Phật Linh Pagoda, a project completed after four
                            years and formally inaugurated in 2009. Since then, he has continued to develop its practice life with the aspiration of
                            establishing a Pure Land practice center for the wider community. He currently also serves as the abbot of Viên Giác Patriarchal
                            Monastery in Hannover, continuing the transmission and organizational work of the monastery in Europe. he belongs to the 42nd
                            generation of the Chúc Thánh branch of the Linji tradition.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </article>

            <article class="rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-6">
                <div class="grid gap-8 md:grid-cols-[260px_1fr] md:items-start">
                    <div class="overflow-hidden rounded-3xl border border-neutral-200 bg-white shadow-sm">
                        <img src="/images/thayhanhgioi.jpg" alt="Thầy Hạnh Giới" class="h-[320px] w-full object-cover object-top" />
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <h2 class="mb-2">Thầy Hạnh Giới</h2>
                        <p class="mb-4 text-neutral-500">Abbot of Viên Lạc Retreat Center, Varel – Germany</p>
                        <p class="leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            Born in 1971, Thầy Hạnh Giới entered monastic life on October 27, 1999, received novice ordination on July 2, 2000, and full bhikshu
                            ordination on March 7, 2002 at the Minh Hải Ordination Platform in Bodh Gaya, India. He belongs to the 42nd generation of the Chúc
                            Thánh branch of the Linji tradition and served as the second abbot of Viên Giác Monastery from 2008 to 2017. He currently serves as
                            abbot of Viên Lạc Retreat Center in Varel, Germany.
                        </p>
                        <p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            Thầy Hạnh Giới is a widely invited Dharma teacher who regularly teaches at practice centers across Europe for both Vietnamese
                            communities and local practitioners. He studied with the Most Venerable Sheng-yen, founder of Dharma Drum Mountain in Taiwan, and is
                            especially known for teaching meditation and Pure Land practice. Fluent in six languages, he brings a broad and accessible teaching
                            style to diverse audiences.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </article>

            <article class="rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-6">
                <div>
                    <div>
                        <h2 class="mb-2">Other Members of the Sangha</h2>
                        <p class="mb-4 text-neutral-500">Supporting and organizing the retreat</p>
                        <p class="leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            In addition to the main teachers, the retreat is supported by other members of the Sangha. Thầy Thông Tuệ,
                            Thầy Thông Kiên, and Sư Cô Thông Chu, who belong to the 43rd generation of the Chúc Thánh branch of the Linji
                            tradition, are the main organizers responsible for communication and coordination of the retreat. They also support
                            participants during the preparation period and throughout the retreat itself.
                        </p>
                        <p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            In addition, there may be other Dharma teachers and Sangha members whose participation has not yet been confirmed. More information
                            will be added in the coming months.
                        </p>
                        <p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            For more information about the monasteries and dharma teachers, visit:
                            <a href="https://viengiac.info">viengiac.info</a>,
                            <a href="https://vienlac.de">vienlac.de</a>,
                            <a href="https://amitayus.net">amitayus.net</a>, and
                            <a href="https://lientam.fi">lientam.fi</a>.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </article>
        </div>
    </section>
</Layout>
